,"question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>300</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c27a4215-adf6-40ff-a161-889e6f5da30f-image.png\" style=\"width: 223px; height: 100px;\" /><br /><br /><math><mi>V</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>l</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mi>M</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>z</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>&#160;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>V</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>&#160;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>o</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>f</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>V</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>e</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>I</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>500</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>500</mn></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>30000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41683,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$\\chi=\\frac{\\mu}{\\mu_0}-1$","$\\chi=\\frac{\\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}}{\\mu_0}+1$","$\\chi=\\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}+1$","$\\chi=1-\\frac{\\mu}{\\mu_0}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"We have<br/>$\\begin{aligned} & \\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}=(1+\\chi) \\Rightarrow \\chi=\\left(\\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}-1\\right) \\\\ & \\mu=\\mu_0 \\mu_{\\mathrm{r}} \\Rightarrow \\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}=\\frac{\\mu}{\\mu_0} \\\\ & \\therefore \\chi=\\left(\\frac{\\mu}{\\mu_0}-1\\right)\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41719,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["a macroscopic region with saturation magnetization.","a macroscopic region with consecutive magnetic dipoles oriented in opposite direction.","a macroscopic region with zero magnetization.","a macroscopic region with randomly oriented magnetic dipoles."],"answer":0,"solution":"In a ferromagnetic material, below the curie temperature, a domain is defined as a macroscopic region with saturation magnetization.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41687,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["(A)-(IV), (B)-(I), (C)-(III), (D)-(II)","(A)-(I), (B)-(III), (C)-(II), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)- (I), (D)-(II)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)"],"answer":3,"solution":"(A) Graph between Magnetic susceptibility and magnetising field is :\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/w6v7neqFdR-CKY5QHXeMsuJNxzt_Ryb_-DT5Kf25Y6E.original.fullsize.png\"><br />(B) magnetic field due to a current carrying wire for $\\mathrm{x} < \\mathrm{a}$ :\n$\\mathrm{B}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{ir}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{a}^2}$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DBbnMu1FS8YbdYjigrdXvHoiKf-CCbi5e4s2Je0eLcs.original.fullsize.png\"><br />(C) magnetic field due to a current carrying wire for $x>a$ :\n$\\mathrm{B}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{i}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{a}}$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rxnQegHyDMRw8sORCOjfmJUPDJg3ujEHQBXAj9yeC1g.original.fullsize.png\"><br />(D) magnetic field inside solenoid varies as:<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1IUO5wNN4u-DehvXVngWe4YIKVVikZ3G1MBjlrf-oCA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41688,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$8 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}$","$4 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}$","Zero","$16 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"At stable equilibrium\n$\\mathrm{U}=-\\mathrm{mB} \\cos 0^{\\circ}=-\\mathrm{mB}$<br />At unstable equilibrium\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{U}=-\\mathrm{mB} \\cos 180^{\\circ}=+\\mathrm{mB} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{W}=\\Delta \\mathrm{U} \\\\\n& \\text { W.D. }=2 \\mathrm{mB} \\\\\n& =2(0.5) 8 \\times 10^{-2}=8 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~J}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41693,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>%</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>It is given that&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>The permeability is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></math>.</p><p>The magnetic field is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></p><p>Hence, percentage increase in magnetic field is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>B</mi></mstyle><mn>0</mn></msub></mstyle><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41756,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["a ferromagnetic material becomes paramagnetic","a paramagnetic material becomes diamagnetic","a ferromagnetic material becomes diamagnetic","a paramagnetic material becomes ferromagnetic"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":41751,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$2 \\mathrm{~s}$","$2 / 3 \\mathrm{~s}$","$2 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~s}$","$2 / \\sqrt{ } 3 \\mathrm{~s}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Time period of vibration, $T=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{M B}}$\nWhere $\\ell=$ moment of inertia of magnet, $\\mathrm{M}=$ magnetic moment $\\mathrm{I}=\\frac{\\mathrm{m} \\ell^2}{12}$ and $\\mathrm{M}=$ pole strength $\\times \\ell$\n$$\nI^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{12}\\left(\\frac{m}{3}\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\ell}{3}\\right)^2 \\times 3=\\frac{\\mathrm{l}}{9}\n$$\nand $M^{\\prime}=$ pole strength (will remain the same) $\\times(\\ell / 3) \\times 3=M$.\n$$\n\\mathrm{T}^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\mathrm{T}}{\\sqrt{9}}=\\frac{2}{9} \\mathrm{~s} .\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41715,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">m</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>500</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Hm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41733,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>&#x3BC;A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>&#x3BC;A</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The coercivity of ferromagnet,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mn>m</mn><mn>A</mn></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":41681,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$\\frac{6}{5} \\times 10^{-3} \\%$","$\\frac{5}{6} \\times 10^{-5} \\%$","$\\frac{5}{6} \\times 10^{-4} \\%$","$\\frac{5}{3} \\times 10^{-5} \\%$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\% \\text { change in } B=\\frac{B_{\\text {new }}-B_{\\text {old }}}{B_{\\text {old }}} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\frac{\\mu \\mathrm{ni}-\\mu_0 \\mathrm{ni}}{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{ni}} \\times 100 \\%=\\frac{\\left(\\mu-\\mu_0\\right)}{\\mu_0} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\frac{\\left(\\mu_0 \\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}-\\mu_0\\right)}{\\mu_0} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\left(\\mu_{\\mathrm{r}}-1\\right) \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =\\chi_{\\mathrm{n}} \\times 100 \\% \\\\ & =1.2 \\times 10^{-3} \\%\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41678,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Let the magnetic moment of each magnet be $M = 3\\sqrt{5}$ J/T.<br><br>The distance of point P from the center of each magnet is $r = 5$ cm $= 0.05$ m.<br><br>For the first magnet (horizontal), point P lies on its axial line. The magnetic field at P due to the first magnet is:<br><br>$B_1 = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{2M}{r^3}$<br><br>The direction of $\\vec{B}_1$ is along the axis of the first magnet.<br><br>For the second magnet (vertical), point P lies on its equatorial line. The magnetic field at P due to the second magnet is:<br><br>$B_2 = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{M}{r^3}$<br><br>The direction of $\\vec{B}_2$ is parallel to the axis of the second magnet, which is perpendicular to the axis of the first magnet.<br><br>Since $\\vec{B}_1$ and $\\vec{B}_2$ are perpendicular to each other, the net magnetic field at P is:<br><br>$B = \\sqrt{B_1^2 + B_2^2}$<br><br>Substituting the expressions for $B_1$ and $B_2$:<br><br>$B = \\sqrt{\\left(\\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{2M}{r^3}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{M}{r^3}\\right)^2}$<br><br>$B = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{M}{r^3} \\sqrt{2^2 + 1^2} = \\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} \\dfrac{\\sqrt{5}M}{r^3}$<br><br>Substituting the given values $\\dfrac{\\mu_0}{4\\pi} = 10^{-7}$ T m/A, $M = 3\\sqrt{5}$ J/T, and $r = 0.05$ m:<br><br>$B = 10^{-7} \\times \\dfrac{\\sqrt{5} \\times 3\\sqrt{5}}{(0.05)^3}$<br><br>$B = 10^{-7} \\times \\dfrac{15}{125 \\times 10^{-6}}$<br><br>$B = \\dfrac{15 \\times 10^{-1}}{125}$<br><br>$B = 0.1 \\times 0.12$ T<br><br>$B = 0.012$ T<br><br>$B = 12 \\times 10^{-3}$ T<br><br>Comparing this with the given value $\\alpha \\times 10^{-3}$ T, we get $\\alpha = 12$.<br><br>Answer: $12$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41730,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.007</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.02</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.014</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0.01</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>As we know that, work done in rotating a magnetic dipole in magnetic field is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>M</mi><mi>B</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Now in the above given question we have, Magnetic Moment&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>,Magnetic Field<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>&nbsp;,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rad</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Let initial angle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;so on reversing the direction of magnetic moment final angle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></math></p><p>Now, substituting all the values in equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;we get,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>&#8757;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>and</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>99</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>W</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p><p>Therefore, the work done in reversing the direction of the magnetic moment is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41699,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b418d024-091f-4ee8-9b8b-c6fdff72575f-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 57px;\" /></p><p>Given here:</p><p>The vertical component of the earths magnetic field&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>&nbsp;and angle of dip&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>37</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p><p>For vertical component,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#948;</mi></math></p><p>Putting the values, we have&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Earth&#39;s magnetic field at that place as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null}]